				\begin{document}$$ \omega = \omega^{*} - k_{P - f} (P - P^{*} ) $$\end{document}2V=V∗-kQ-V(Q-Q∗)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ V = V^{*} - k_{Q - V} (Q - Q^{*} ) $$\end{document}where ω and V are the frequency and amplitude of the output voltage measurement; ω* and V* are the frequency and voltage references; P and Q are the active power and reactive power measurements; P* and Q* are the active and reactive power references; kP-f and kQ-V are the proportional gain for the P-f and Q-V droop characteristics, respectively.Fig. 7
P-f and Q-V droop control relationship in AC MGs [20]

